So I, I don't know, I've written a lot of books about R now, but I would say

00:12:03.320 --> 00:12:07.039
like, you know, I think of like R for data science is like, if you're, you

00:12:07.039 --> 00:12:10.840
know, if you want to learn how to do data science in R. Advanced R is if

00:12:10.840 --> 00:12:14.960
you want to learn how R works as a programming language, and there's kind

00:12:14.960 --> 00:12:19.000
of this gap in between them, like, how do you go from, you know, someone

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:24.440
being just a, you know, a data scientist who is analyzing like individual

00:12:25.159 --> 00:12:28.799
to someone who's starting to design like kind of bigger pieces of code, like

00:12:28.799 --> 00:12:34.239
functions that you can use and multiple analysis, or maybe eventually you

00:12:34.239 --> 00:12:35.679
collect enough of those functions.

00:12:35.679 --> 00:12:36.840
Do you want to do a package?

00:12:37.400 --> 00:12:40.440
So like, how do you, like when you're writing a function, like,

00:12:40.799 --> 00:12:41.960
what do you think about?

00:12:41.960 --> 00:12:45.000
Like, how do you, like, how do you pick the arguments?

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:46.359
