00:14:57.119 --> 00:15:03.440
When you design packages, how do you factor in security given the increasing

00:15:03.440 --> 00:15:07.359
number of hacking and other attacks that are happening in the enterprise

00:15:07.359 --> 00:15:08.440
space these days?

00:15:08.840 --> 00:15:09.320
Thank you.

00:15:09.880 --> 00:15:14.400
Yeah, I would, security is a difficult, a difficult one because I think in most,

00:15:14.440 --> 00:15:18.479
like most of the tidyverse, it just doesn't like really apply.

00:15:18.479 --> 00:15:23.359
Like, you know, you don't have to worry about security and ggpoc2, for example.

00:15:24.200 --> 00:15:29.200
Like we think about it more in the packages that have to require authentication.

00:15:29.799 --> 00:15:33.400
So typically, you know, when you're getting data, whether it's from an API or

00:15:33.400 --> 00:15:38.280
a database, you are going to need to have a security protocol that's going to

00:15:38.640 --> 00:15:42.440
need to store those credentials somehow.

00:15:42.760 --> 00:15:46.239
And one of the things I've been thinking about in particular recently, as I've

00:15:46.239 --> 00:15:51.119
been working more on like using our pro products is like you, how do you make

00:15:51.119 --> 00:15:57.320
sure those credentials travel kind of both seamlessly and securely from wherever

00:15:57.320 --> 00:16:01.760
you're doing the analysis to wherever you're deploying the analysis?

00:16:02.159 --> 00:16:06.039
So currently I think we're at the stage where it's a lot around like, how do we

00:16:06.039 --> 00:16:08.919
help our users learn the right conventions?

00:16:08.919 --> 00:16:14.159
Like you should never be typing your password into the console because if you

00:16:14.159 --> 00:16:19.679
do that, it's easy for it to end up saved in your data history file and it's easy

00:16:19.679 --> 00:16:23.599
to accidentally commit that to get, and now you've shared your password with a

00:16:23.599 --> 00:16:26.239
much wider range of people than you should be.

00:16:27.400 --> 00:16:31.280
So at the moment, there's I think a lot of use of environment variables, which

00:16:31.280 --> 00:16:35.919
are a little bit safer, at least because you're not storing them literally in

00:16:36.039 --> 00:16:43.960
your code, but how can we do better at, you know, providing tools for saving

00:16:43.960 --> 00:16:48.000
those securely and then when needed, like sharing them across from your

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.960
computer to connect or to Shiny apps or whatever.

00:16:51.599 --> 00:16:55.599
So I think lots of questions there, not a lot of answers currently.

00:16:58.919 --> 00:17:01.840
Sanjay, I see you had a question in the chat earlier too.

00:17:01.840 --> 00:17:02.840
Do you want to jump in here?

00:17:03.679 --> 00:17:04.199
Yeah.

00:17:04.520 --> 00:17:05.119
Hi Hadley.

00:17:05.839 --> 00:17:10.880
One thing which always intrigued me is our company always looked at purchasing

00:17:10.880 --> 00:17:16.800
the Post-it RStudio Connect or Post-it Connect, but we never got a proper sales

00:17:16.800 --> 00:17:23.079
pitch and could you articulate what advantages Post-it RStudio Connect has

00:17:23.079 --> 00:17:25.319
over the open source version, please?

00:17:26.599 --> 00:17:26.839
Yeah.

00:17:26.839 --> 00:17:33.760
So I would say like the reason why you want Connect or it's kind of like main

00:17:33.760 --> 00:17:40.520
value proposition to me is it helps get your data analyses out of the hands of

00:17:40.520 --> 00:17:45.760
data scientists and into the hands of decision makers and at the end of the

00:17:45.760 --> 00:17:49.599
day, like it doesn't matter how awesome you are as a data scientist, unless you

00:17:49.599 --> 00:17:54.439
can show your results to people, your analyses to people in your organization

00:17:54.439 --> 00:17:58.800
who actually need them and so Connect is really about like publishing whatever

00:17:58.839 --> 00:18:04.560
you're doing in R to a form that other people in your organization can see,

00:18:04.560 --> 00:18:09.160
whether that's like Shiny apps or RMark or Quota documents, or if you want to

00:18:09.160 --> 00:18:13.319
turn those into like a scheduled report so that people are getting emailed at

00:18:13.319 --> 00:18:17.119
9am every day with the latest results in your dashboard, it's all about like

00:18:17.119 --> 00:18:23.520
sharing what you're doing as a data scientist and ideally like the goal of

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:26.880
Connect, which we're not like a hundred percent of the way there, but we're

00:18:26.880 --> 00:18:30.839
trying to get there in the long run, very much the goal is going to do that

00:18:30.839 --> 00:18:34.760
just by like pushing a button in your RStudio, wherever you're doing the

00:18:34.760 --> 00:18:39.239
analysis, it should just be a single click or a single function call to get

00:18:39.239 --> 00:18:45.199
that up so you can stay focused on the, you know, the data analysis rather than

00:18:45.199 --> 00:18:48.800
having to worry about like running a web server, securing a web server, make

00:18:48.800 --> 00:18:53.920
sure all the authentication is working, make sure your email jobs are getting

00:18:53.959 --> 00:18:57.119
sent out correctly, and when those jobs fail, that you get notified that they

00:18:57.119 --> 00:19:01.319
didn't work and all that kind of other stuff, which is like really necessary

00:19:01.319 --> 00:19:05.119
for a product like this to work, but probably you don't care about as a data

00:19:05.119 --> 00:19:09.239
scientist and thinking about it just gets in the way of doing your, doing

00:19:09.239 --> 00:19:10.280
your most important work.

00:19:11.439 --> 00:19:17.719
But quite a lot of it is achieved from RStudio open source server also, isn't it?

00:19:17.959 --> 00:19:18.199
Right.

00:19:18.199 --> 00:19:22.199
Like, yes, like you could be doing the analysis and the open source products,

00:19:22.199 --> 00:19:25.520
but there's no open source tool that's quite the same as Kinect.

00:19:25.560 --> 00:19:29.520
You can certainly string it together with a bunch of different open source

00:19:29.520 --> 00:19:35.119
products, but I think our belief would be it's going to cost you much less time

00:19:35.119 --> 00:19:40.119
and much less money to just buy this thing that we have built where the cost

00:19:40.119 --> 00:19:44.800
of building it is amortized over thousands of customers rather than you

00:19:44.800 --> 00:19:49.280
having to pay that cost yourself by developing the open source solutions

00:19:49.280 --> 00:19:49.959
from scratch.

00:19:50.800 --> 00:19:51.359
Got it.

00:19:51.680 --> 00:19:52.160
Thank you.

00:19:53.199 --> 00:19:53.719
Awesome.

00:19:53.719 --> 00:19:54.319
Thank you.

00:19:54.680 --> 00:19:56.959
Thank you for all these great questions coming in.

00:19:57.479 --> 00:20:01.640
Libby, I see you just asked one that is getting so many hearts and reactions

00:20:01.640 --> 00:20:04.439
right now, so I'm going to have you jump in here to ask that.

00:20:05.319 --> 00:20:05.839
Sure.

00:20:05.880 --> 00:20:08.359
I'm always swooping in with the touchy feely questions.

00:20:09.800 --> 00:20:15.359
When JJ was on, he gave you a lot of credit for the culture at RStudio, now

00:20:15.359 --> 00:20:20.479
posit, and so I was kind of wondering if there was anything that you did, any

00:20:20.839 --> 00:20:26.079
steps that you took to kind of make sure that RStudio moved that direction or

00:20:26.079 --> 00:20:29.719
kind of could embody the stuff that you hoped culture wise.

00:20:31.160 --> 00:20:35.680
I'm laughing just because I think that's like classic JJ, because I think he's

00:20:35.920 --> 00:20:43.479
way more responsible for the culture than I am, but I will say, I think the

00:20:43.479 --> 00:20:53.079
thing that both JJ and I share is that I think like, while we are both like

00:20:53.079 --> 00:20:57.680
really good programmers, that we don't believe that makes us like better human

00:20:57.680 --> 00:21:01.439
beings in any way, just a skill that we happen to have.

00:21:01.920 --> 00:21:06.560
And that I think, you know, as people with these skills, it's our responsibility

00:21:06.560 --> 00:21:09.199
to help the people that we can help with them.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:15.560
And it's just been so wonderful working with JJ and Tareef and the whole

00:21:15.560 --> 00:21:18.880
leadership team at Posit over the last 10 years, because I think that those

00:21:18.880 --> 00:21:25.160
values are really strongly instilled now in our company culture, that like we

00:21:25.160 --> 00:21:26.640
try and do the right thing.

00:21:26.880 --> 00:21:32.800
You know, we're a B Corp because we don't want to optimize for short term

00:21:32.800 --> 00:21:37.280
profits, we want to be in this for the long term, we want to be able to make

00:21:37.680 --> 00:21:43.920
the right decisions that help us out in the community out in the long term, not

00:21:43.920 --> 00:21:46.599
just do what's exigent in the moment.

00:21:47.560 --> 00:21:48.000
Thank you.

00:21:48.479 --> 00:21:48.760
Okay.

00:21:48.760 --> 00:21:55.479
Jumping over to one on Slido is what gaps do you see in the R ecosystem?

00:21:55.520 --> 00:21:59.400
For example, most deep learning and AI applications are built with

00:21:59.400 --> 00:22:01.439
PyTorch, SensorFlow and Keras.

00:22:01.719 --> 00:22:03.079
Do you see R catching up?

00:22:04.079 --> 00:22:07.040
Yeah, I don't see R catching up there.

00:22:07.040 --> 00:22:13.400
I think the Python, there's just such a huge community there that R is

00:22:13.479 --> 00:22:15.920
never going to catch up and that's fine.

00:22:15.920 --> 00:22:18.239
Like R doesn't have to be good at everything.

00:22:18.280 --> 00:22:19.880
R is not Python.

00:22:20.520 --> 00:22:24.599
R can be good at like a set of really important tasks.

00:22:24.599 --> 00:22:26.000
It doesn't have to embrace everything.

00:22:26.680 --> 00:22:31.359
And it can do that because, you know, R is fundamentally the sort of glue

00:22:31.359 --> 00:22:36.640
language that there's no sense amongst R users that R must be the only language

00:22:36.640 --> 00:22:41.880
you use, you use it as much as it helps you and then you use the tools like

00:22:41.880 --> 00:22:46.400
reticulate to talk to Python or a lot of the building stuff for talking to C and

00:22:46.400 --> 00:22:52.359
C++ and new stuff for talking to Rust and Go that, you know, you talk to whatever

00:22:52.359 --> 00:22:57.160
systems your data lives in from R and then you benefit from this environment

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:03.680
that I believe is just unparalleled for fluid, interactive data exploration.

00:23:04.479 --> 00:23:07.920
Jesse, I see you had a question in the chat a bit earlier.

00:23:07.920 --> 00:23:08.920
Do you want to jump in here?

00:23:09.599 --> 00:23:13.520
And at some point, because we have so many, I might need to say first and last names.

00:23:14.839 --> 00:23:16.000
But it's Jesse Osman.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:17.800
I can ask, I can ask the question.

00:23:17.800 --> 00:23:19.839
If you want to add any context, feel free.

00:23:20.880 --> 00:23:26.239
But the question was when writing books using Cordo, are there any helper packages

00:23:26.239 --> 00:23:31.680
that you would use to help format those files to actually look like books and how

00:23:31.680 --> 00:23:33.959
do you get those Cordo files print ready?

00:23:34.079 --> 00:23:36.000
Yeah, that's a good question.

00:23:36.079 --> 00:23:41.839
And the answer depends a lot on kind of exactly what your target is for the

00:23:41.839 --> 00:23:44.160
book and kind of where your skills lie.

00:23:44.199 --> 00:23:49.000
So like for the cocktail book, that's self-published, hopefully, obviously

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:53.400
there's no, I'm not signing up with cocktail book publishers.

00:23:53.479 --> 00:23:59.520
And I did that, a lot of that is kind of custom, like it uses Cordo, but it a lot of

00:23:59.520 --> 00:24:08.199
customization with LaTeX using my limited LaTeX skills and much Googling and some

00:24:08.560 --> 00:24:11.359
GPT to get things working.

00:24:14.920 --> 00:24:18.839
But other stuff like the, like if you're publishing with O'Reilly, now Cordo can

00:24:18.839 --> 00:24:21.439
output the ASCII doc, which is what O'Reilly uses.

00:24:21.760 --> 00:24:26.359
Other publishers, like more scientific publishers, you will need to create a PDF

00:24:26.359 --> 00:24:30.880
typically using LaTeX and then you'll need to do some customization yourself.

00:24:31.280 --> 00:24:40.040
I think like that, that, that tool chain from LaTeX to PDF is kind of still the best

00:24:40.040 --> 00:24:41.079
formed route.

00:24:41.800 --> 00:24:44.560
Obviously it requires some understanding of LaTeX.

00:24:45.359 --> 00:24:52.599
I will say that it is both like impossible to gain any meaningful understanding of

00:24:52.599 --> 00:24:54.920
LaTeX without probably decades of work.

00:24:55.199 --> 00:25:00.239
But fortunately, like Googling and copying and pasting and some fair amount of

00:25:00.239 --> 00:25:04.239
frustration will typically find what you want, because pretty much everything you

00:25:04.239 --> 00:25:05.520
want, someone has already done.

00:25:05.920 --> 00:25:08.880
And it's just a matter of like finding the right snippet to paste in and hope it

00:25:08.880 --> 00:25:11.640
doesn't conflict with the other snippet you pasted in.

00:25:12.400 --> 00:25:16.680
I think like, like LaTeX is definitely in the past.

00:25:16.680 --> 00:25:22.280
I think we're seeing kind of more tools like Pagedown where you can render like,

00:25:22.599 --> 00:25:26.560
you know, PDF kind of quality outputs using HTML engines.

00:25:27.239 --> 00:25:32.160
That, you know, I think solves one set of problems and introduces another.

00:25:32.160 --> 00:25:35.000
Now you've got to learn some like CSS for customization.

00:25:35.520 --> 00:25:38.560
But I think we'll see more and more of that in the future.

00:25:39.560 --> 00:25:45.280
I also just don't really think about like, I still think like the primary version of

00:25:45.280 --> 00:25:46.760
my books is the online version.

00:25:46.760 --> 00:25:50.160
I think that is what most people read.

00:25:50.160 --> 00:25:54.000
And I just think about the physical books as kind of like a nice offshoot that I

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:58.959
don't, I honestly don't really care about because I do not read physical books

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:03.959
anymore. So I know, I know some people do and it's nice to have them, but it's

00:26:03.959 --> 00:26:06.680
just the online version I think is so much more important.

00:26:07.040 --> 00:26:11.160
I love all of this conversation happening in the chat right now, too.

00:26:11.160 --> 00:26:15.000
And just want to say, if you're joining us for the first time, that's where a lot of

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:19.119
people end up meeting each other, too, and like sharing helpful links with each other,

00:26:19.119 --> 00:26:21.479
too. So feel free to jump in there.

00:26:21.719 --> 00:26:25.560
And thank you to the Posit folks in the back end who are helping me pull out some of

00:26:25.560 --> 00:26:27.079
the questions from there.

