Alan, I see you had asked, oh, sorry, you go ahead.

00:26:31.359 --> 00:26:32.359
Can I pull one out?

00:26:32.479 --> 00:26:33.479
Yeah, go ahead.

00:26:33.479 --> 00:26:39.280
I was going to ask you about these, which are actually

00:26:40.040 --> 00:26:43.800
embroidery, Higgs Logos by Sharla

00:26:44.959 --> 00:26:46.680
Galvan. So I have a lot of

00:26:50.479 --> 00:26:55.359
things like that, that you might see my like a Hershey distribution,

00:26:56.160 --> 00:26:58.680
Halloween, blushy.

00:26:59.199 --> 00:27:05.079
I'm thinking back to the hex dress

00:27:05.079 --> 00:27:09.560
that I saw at the RStudio conference one time, all the amazing things people make

00:27:09.800 --> 00:27:10.800
with the hexes.

00:27:11.760 --> 00:27:16.599
I think the most impressive conflated thing I saw was

00:27:16.599 --> 00:27:21.640
like someone had like tidyverse hexes painted on their nails

00:27:22.359 --> 00:27:26.439
that they'd done themselves. But that was really, really impressive to do it that

00:27:26.439 --> 00:27:27.439
small.

00:27:28.280 --> 00:27:29.280
Absolutely.

00:27:30.400 --> 00:27:34.239
Alan, I see you had a question here in the chat, do you want to jump in?

00:27:34.959 --> 00:27:39.560
I do. I put in a couple, Rachel, are you eyeballing a specific one?

00:27:40.839 --> 00:27:45.119
You could ask your favorite one, but I see that people were

00:27:46.439 --> 00:27:48.359
upvoting your B Corp question.

00:27:48.439 --> 00:27:50.520
I'll go with the most recent one, yeah, the B Corp one.

00:27:50.520 --> 00:27:54.959
I'm curious, Hadley, if in the B Corp landscape, are there

00:27:55.640 --> 00:28:00.719
peers that look like Posit are doing similar things or are you alone?

00:28:00.719 --> 00:28:06.000
And what's that like to either have some sort of well-trod ground to follow

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:10.680
or is it figuring out like every day, like strategically, what does Posit as a B

00:28:10.680 --> 00:28:12.439
Corp do in this kind of situation?

00:28:12.439 --> 00:28:16.920
And I'm sort of curious if that's like liberating or if it's terrifying,

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:21.599
like what's that like kind of to think about operationally being in that space?

00:28:21.959 --> 00:28:27.560
I'd say we do some benchmarking against other B Corps

00:28:27.560 --> 00:28:31.280
and the places where benchmarks are typically available.

00:28:31.280 --> 00:28:35.119
Like I know we do like our employee kind of satisfaction surveys.

00:28:35.119 --> 00:28:38.359
We benchmark those against other B Corps.

00:28:39.119 --> 00:28:40.599
But I don't.

00:28:42.520 --> 00:28:46.400
I mean, I don't really know if there are B Corps like us.

00:28:46.400 --> 00:28:47.719
I suspect there are not.

00:28:47.719 --> 00:28:51.359
There are just not that many like software B Corps that are not

00:28:51.359 --> 00:28:54.119
that many open source companies.

00:28:54.119 --> 00:28:57.479
And I guess that I don't know,

00:28:57.959 --> 00:29:01.839
that feels kind of like more freeing to me than worrying.

00:29:02.839 --> 00:29:05.800
You know, certainly a lot of what we do is just a standard.

00:29:05.920 --> 00:29:10.880
You know, there's a lot of it's just kind of standard software business playbook.

00:29:12.400 --> 00:29:15.640
But at the same time, we don't have this like

00:29:16.199 --> 00:29:20.560
more about removing this drive to optimize short term profitability

00:29:21.040 --> 00:29:23.800
that gives us the room to kind of,

00:29:25.439 --> 00:29:28.839
you know, do the things that we believe to be right.

00:29:29.160 --> 00:29:30.400
You know, as much as possible.

00:29:30.400 --> 00:29:34.439
It's not always possible to, you know, it's like what is right

00:29:34.439 --> 00:29:37.760
is a very complicated question, especially as the size of a company grows.

00:29:38.199 --> 00:29:41.400
But certainly we you know, we we have more freedom

00:29:41.400 --> 00:29:43.439
to kind of think about that and act on that.

00:29:43.479 --> 00:29:46.520
And while, you know, certainly we still make mistakes,

00:29:46.520 --> 00:29:49.839
I think everyone is, you know, trying to try their absolute best.

00:29:50.079 --> 00:29:51.439
Thanks. Appreciate that.

00:29:51.439 --> 00:29:55.359
And where is I see you ask the question here in the chat.

00:29:55.400 --> 00:29:57.400
You want to jump in next?

00:29:57.479 --> 00:30:00.719
Sure. I'll hop on real quick and good effort on the last name.

00:30:01.880 --> 00:30:03.439
Oh, sorry.

00:30:03.439 --> 00:30:05.199
Can you tell me how to say it?

00:30:05.199 --> 00:30:08.119
It's like Ferris. Just OK.

00:30:08.119 --> 00:30:11.439
So you've taken a lot of solutions to massive pain points

00:30:11.439 --> 00:30:13.119
that are challenging and non-obvious.

00:30:15.079 --> 00:30:18.239
I know if I tried to do something like GG plot,

00:30:18.439 --> 00:30:21.439
I would make no progress whatsoever.

00:30:21.439 --> 00:30:25.479
So I wonder, how do you find your starting points for implementation?

00:30:25.479 --> 00:30:28.359
Like, where do you start from and how do you measure your progress

00:30:28.359 --> 00:30:30.280
and make sure you're moving towards your end goal?

00:30:30.280 --> 00:30:32.239
Good question.

00:30:34.800 --> 00:30:36.800
It feels like a lot of.

00:30:38.079 --> 00:30:40.479
The packages that I work on just have this

00:30:41.319 --> 00:30:44.199
the sense of inevitability about them,

00:30:44.199 --> 00:30:47.199
that these are just things that like frustrate me

00:30:47.199 --> 00:30:50.839
and typically have frustrated me for years before, like some

00:30:51.439 --> 00:30:54.280
kind of solution crystallizes in my head.

00:30:54.880 --> 00:30:59.040
And then it's just a matter of like a lot of iteration.

00:30:59.560 --> 00:31:03.079
And, you know, now I think one of the huge

00:31:03.760 --> 00:31:07.439
advantages I have is that, you know, there's a there's a community of people

00:31:07.959 --> 00:31:11.880
who are willing to try out like whatever crap I produce

00:31:12.280 --> 00:31:16.959
and give me like feedback and tell me like, you know, this doesn't work

00:31:16.959 --> 00:31:20.119
or this, I don't understand this or this is inconsistent

00:31:20.119 --> 00:31:22.119
with a lot of our Tidyverse thing.

00:31:22.119 --> 00:31:27.400
And that is just I find that that kind of interaction, like personally,

00:31:27.400 --> 00:31:32.119
like, you know, highly motivating that people care when people care enough

00:31:32.760 --> 00:31:35.520
to like critique it.

00:31:35.520 --> 00:31:38.239
I find that to be, yeah, really motivating.

00:31:38.239 --> 00:31:40.959
So I think that that is just that.

00:31:40.959 --> 00:31:44.760
And some weird part of my brain that is just like collecting

00:31:44.760 --> 00:31:49.119
these little pain points and after a while realizing that all of these pain

00:31:49.119 --> 00:31:53.199
points, like maybe there's some root cause that I could fix all at once.

00:31:53.839 --> 00:31:58.040
Other times it's like, let's just, you know, knock them off one by one

00:31:58.040 --> 00:32:01.000
and then hope something falls out.

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:06.160
Yeah, and it's just this, I still feel like a lot of packages,

00:32:06.160 --> 00:32:10.400
it just feels like I feel like there's a sort of compulsion to create them

00:32:10.400 --> 00:32:14.239
that occurs inside of me at some point in my life.

00:32:14.560 --> 00:32:16.199
Right. So it feels like you're a force of nature then.

00:32:18.319 --> 00:32:21.560
So a Slido question somebody had asked was,

00:32:21.959 --> 00:32:28.040
do you have any recommendations for teaching non-coder data generators

00:32:28.040 --> 00:32:30.640
that it's good to use tidy structured data

00:32:30.959 --> 00:32:33.719
so we can use their data so much more easily?

00:32:35.239 --> 00:32:37.839
Yeah, I think the.

00:32:37.839 --> 00:32:40.800
I feel like the challenge of teaching anything like this is always

00:32:40.800 --> 00:32:43.800
you have to figure out what are the benefits to them,

00:32:44.199 --> 00:32:47.040
not what are the benefits to you, because the benefits to you

00:32:47.040 --> 00:32:51.160
are typically very obvious, but are not motivating to other people.

00:32:51.439 --> 00:32:55.680
So you need to figure out, like, what's some angle where by adopting

00:32:55.680 --> 00:32:59.760
these new ideas, can they save themselves work

00:33:00.239 --> 00:33:02.160
or can they produce something cool?

00:33:02.160 --> 00:33:05.400
And maybe that's like if it's not about saving,

00:33:05.400 --> 00:33:07.920
if you can't find any way that it's going to save them work,

00:33:08.359 --> 00:33:10.640
maybe there's something you can do with the tidy data

00:33:10.640 --> 00:33:14.839
automatically to produce some kind of useful plot or motivating figure

00:33:14.839 --> 00:33:19.520
that will kind of help them say like, oh, this is, you know, this is kind of fun.

00:33:20.160 --> 00:33:23.959
So I think, yeah, like try and make it easier or try and make it more fun.

00:33:24.719 --> 00:33:25.839
Anything else?

00:33:25.839 --> 00:33:29.640
Like it's a hard, it's a hard road to get other people

00:33:29.959 --> 00:33:32.239
to change their minds and to change their processes.

00:33:33.119 --> 00:33:35.760
David Meza, I see you asked a question in the chat.

00:33:35.760 --> 00:33:37.239
You want to jump in here next?

00:33:37.239 --> 00:33:38.319
I did, and I apologize.

00:33:38.319 --> 00:33:39.560
My video is not working.

