Hey.

00:33:43.640 --> 00:33:45.119
One of the questions, I had two questions.

00:33:45.119 --> 00:33:47.359
One of them was around tidy models and better work.

00:33:48.239 --> 00:33:52.040
They've done a lot of good work on trying to expand the MLOps

00:33:52.040 --> 00:33:53.760
in an organization.

00:33:53.760 --> 00:33:56.520
Any thoughts about what may be happening in the future?

00:33:56.520 --> 00:33:59.760
How do we can get better MLOps in organizations using Fawcett?

00:33:59.959 --> 00:34:01.880
Yeah, that's a good question.

00:34:01.880 --> 00:34:06.079
I mean, I think our sort of hope is like as we get better

00:34:06.079 --> 00:34:09.560
at integrating our open source tools and our professional tools,

00:34:09.560 --> 00:34:12.280
some of that will just kind of happen naturally.

00:34:12.280 --> 00:34:14.560
I think that's, you know, one of the things we are struggling with,

00:34:14.919 --> 00:34:18.600
struggle with as an organization is like, how do we help these

00:34:18.600 --> 00:34:21.760
like fairly disparate teams with quite different cultures?

00:34:21.760 --> 00:34:24.800
Like work together and create solutions that, you know,

00:34:24.800 --> 00:34:27.320
work for people out in the real world.

00:34:27.320 --> 00:34:31.120
So I think that that sort of feels to me like where the missing pieces are.

00:34:31.120 --> 00:34:36.439
Like we want to deliver these like end to end solutions which like just work.

00:34:36.919 --> 00:34:41.280
And if we can, you know, make model deployment really easy,

00:34:41.280 --> 00:34:45.040
model deployment and monitoring really easy for you, hopefully people will use it more.

00:34:45.439 --> 00:34:46.439
Thank you.

00:34:46.439 --> 00:34:54.120
I think a lot of chat about Hex tattoos, different Paws in our studio tattoos in there.

