Nice.

00:35:17.040 --> 00:35:18.560
Let's see.

00:35:18.560 --> 00:35:20.360
So many great questions here.

00:35:20.360 --> 00:35:23.040
I'm trying to get to everybody's.

00:35:23.040 --> 00:35:27.159
I see Jake, you asked, Jake Riley, you asked a question here in the chat.

00:35:27.800 --> 00:35:28.800
Oh, yeah.

00:35:29.280 --> 00:35:31.439
I know that there's other packages under the tidyverse,

00:35:31.439 --> 00:35:34.399
like lubridate was a separate package that you would have to load

00:35:34.399 --> 00:35:35.959
instead of tidyverse, but it's not included.

00:35:35.959 --> 00:35:38.800
I was curious how you pick which packages come along.

00:35:39.159 --> 00:35:40.479
And I'm hoping glue is next.

00:35:41.159 --> 00:35:46.360
Glue is not next because you can already kind of get to it using STR.

00:35:46.600 --> 00:35:49.719
Glue, because that's re-imported through.

00:35:50.840 --> 00:35:53.239
Like glue is a little bit of a tricky candidate

00:35:53.239 --> 00:35:55.239
because it was kind of designed to be.

00:35:58.120 --> 00:35:59.120
Well, maybe.

00:36:00.159 --> 00:36:03.600
Yeah, I think glue, I don't know, glue just feels like too small.

00:36:04.760 --> 00:36:08.719
To be like at this level, especially when you can get to like 95%

00:36:08.719 --> 00:36:11.879
of the functionality by STR underscore glue.

00:36:12.560 --> 00:36:17.639
So generally, I think like the tidyverse now is like,

00:36:17.639 --> 00:36:21.639
I don't see any much likelihood that membership is going to change

00:36:22.719 --> 00:36:24.639
the next couple of years just because lubridate,

00:36:24.639 --> 00:36:28.040
that's been a goal to get lubridate in the tidyverse, but.

00:36:29.360 --> 00:36:32.679
Yeah, like something like five years now, and finally,

00:36:32.679 --> 00:36:35.879
kind of all the like various bits that we had to deprecate and fix

00:36:35.879 --> 00:36:39.959
in various places kind of felt mature enough, we could pull the trigger on that.

00:36:40.439 --> 00:36:42.679
But so for something else to be added to the tidyverse,

00:36:42.679 --> 00:36:44.840
like we'd have to be, you know, start work now.

00:36:44.840 --> 00:36:47.120
And it would happen in a couple of years.

00:36:47.120 --> 00:36:49.199
And there's nothing on the on the table currently.

00:36:49.760 --> 00:36:53.679
Ben asked a question, I think Ben maybe had to drop for another call,

00:36:53.679 --> 00:36:55.479
but so I'll ask it.

00:36:55.479 --> 00:36:59.840
But the question was, while I'm bought into developing open source packages

00:36:59.840 --> 00:37:03.760
to help deliver better processes, any advice to those of us

00:37:03.760 --> 00:37:07.479
doing that development in getting their company buy in?

00:37:08.199 --> 00:37:13.040
Again, it's like, how do you like, you've got to give some benefit

00:37:13.040 --> 00:37:15.199
to the people using this.

00:37:16.679 --> 00:37:21.879
And you've got to like either remove pain or add pleasure in some way,

00:37:22.280 --> 00:37:26.800
because if you can't do that and you're not someone's like direct supervisor

00:37:26.919 --> 00:37:30.840
with a lot of direct power over them, it's hard to get people to change.

00:37:30.840 --> 00:37:33.919
So I think like to me, a lot of it's like,

00:37:34.399 --> 00:37:36.320
well, the way I think about the tidyverse is like,

00:37:36.320 --> 00:37:40.719
how do we give people some sort of like quick wins

00:37:41.080 --> 00:37:44.719
so they can be motivated to do the stuff that are like slower,

00:37:44.719 --> 00:37:47.040
where they're going to have to learn more,

00:37:47.040 --> 00:37:50.159
like learn some new ideas or some new tools

00:37:51.399 --> 00:37:56.040
so that you kind of build up some kind of equity with that person.

00:37:56.040 --> 00:37:58.719
Like they build up some trust that you've helped them in the past.

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:02.120
And now they're willing to invest like a little bit more time

00:38:02.239 --> 00:38:04.120
before they see the payoff.

00:38:04.120 --> 00:38:06.399
But in the early days, it's all about like, you know,

00:38:06.399 --> 00:38:08.879
delivering payoffs as quickly as possible.

00:38:09.360 --> 00:38:13.760
And I think if you're doing like you're like my company's first package,

00:38:13.760 --> 00:38:18.399
like the easy pain points are like make themes

00:38:18.399 --> 00:38:22.600
for your company corporate style guide, like make a GG.2 theme,

00:38:22.959 --> 00:38:27.239
make an R Markdown, a core theme, make a shiny theme that people can just use

00:38:27.520 --> 00:38:29.719
to get, you know, something that's reasonably close

00:38:29.719 --> 00:38:32.360
to whatever your corporate style guide dictates.

00:38:32.679 --> 00:38:35.520
And that's just like that just feels like an easy win for people

00:38:35.520 --> 00:38:39.000
because it makes them look good inside the corporation.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:42.679
And because you've put in all this hard work, it's like three seconds

00:38:42.679 --> 00:38:45.320
for them to type the right function and to get the right theme.

00:38:46.679 --> 00:38:51.280
And I think the other bit is like make it easy to get access to data.

00:38:52.919 --> 00:38:57.080
Like so set up some wrappers around DBI connections

00:38:57.080 --> 00:39:01.120
to the most important data sources, provide some conventions

00:39:01.120 --> 00:39:05.800
around authentication so that stuff just works so that they're not like

00:39:05.800 --> 00:39:07.120
you're not struggling.

00:39:07.120 --> 00:39:09.239
Like, how do I what package do I need to install?

00:39:09.239 --> 00:39:10.239
Like, what's the password?

00:39:10.239 --> 00:39:12.000
Where's the path I need?

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:17.239
Just give them some like a list of the top ten most common data sources.

00:39:17.800 --> 00:39:21.800
And like people will love you by and large.

00:39:22.919 --> 00:39:24.800
Thank you, Brittany, I see your hands raised.

00:39:24.800 --> 00:39:25.879
You want to jump in here next?

00:39:27.080 --> 00:39:30.560
Yeah, I actually had a similar question that then and I'm maybe

00:39:30.560 --> 00:39:31.600
trying to phrase a little differently.

00:39:31.600 --> 00:39:36.080
So when you are thinking about sort of developing maybe that first package

00:39:36.080 --> 00:39:39.560
for your company or something of that nature, once you've identified

00:39:39.560 --> 00:39:43.520
the things that you think would be useful for people, do you have

00:39:43.520 --> 00:39:47.560
like a philosophy or a way in which you approach kind of putting things

00:39:47.560 --> 00:39:50.360
together? Because I know one of the pain points is as you're developing,

00:39:50.360 --> 00:39:54.959
you realize, oh, what I did originally doesn't quite work and not to tear

00:39:54.959 --> 00:39:56.639
it down and kind of build it back up again.

00:39:57.080 --> 00:40:00.760
So I don't know if you have lessons learned from developing so many

00:40:00.760 --> 00:40:02.120
packages that we could learn from.

00:40:03.239 --> 00:40:08.040
Yeah, that's I think that's a tough one, because I think.

00:40:09.120 --> 00:40:13.399
Like as a team, we have got like vastly better at dealing with kind

00:40:13.399 --> 00:40:18.199
of deprecations and breakages, and I was reminded of this recently

00:40:18.199 --> 00:40:22.639
because I had to rebuild the first edition of Alpha Data Science and

00:40:22.639 --> 00:40:26.199
it just works like five years later, all the code in that book still

00:40:26.199 --> 00:40:28.639
works, which is certainly not like true.

00:40:28.639 --> 00:40:31.679
Like five years ago, if you tried to do that with five years of code

00:40:31.679 --> 00:40:33.000
in the tidy, it wouldn't have worked.

00:40:34.360 --> 00:40:38.120
And, you know, I think that that that's obviously great to have that,

00:40:38.120 --> 00:40:42.879
but it's also like a huge amount of extra work to do that.

00:40:43.280 --> 00:40:45.919
And like we can kind of afford to spend that work.

00:40:45.919 --> 00:40:50.360
And now we're a team of like, you know, at least my team is like six

00:40:50.360 --> 00:40:54.000
plus full time people who can spend our time thinking about this,

00:40:54.800 --> 00:40:58.199
because I think there's really like when you're in an environment of

00:40:58.199 --> 00:41:01.639
like scarcity, when you've only got like so much time that you can

00:41:01.639 --> 00:41:06.120
take out of your kind of like everyday job to invest in writing a package.

00:41:06.639 --> 00:41:08.399
Like it's really tough to balance.

00:41:08.399 --> 00:41:12.000
Like, how do I like add new stuff versus making sure the

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:14.360
old stuff continues to work?

00:41:15.560 --> 00:41:18.679
So I don't have any great advice there.

00:41:18.879 --> 00:41:23.959
I think, again, some of it's about coming like building up trust.

00:41:23.959 --> 00:41:28.919
So like give people some wins so that when you do inevitably break stuff

00:41:28.919 --> 00:41:33.360
like accidentally or on Christmas, you've got some like kind of cushion

00:41:33.360 --> 00:41:36.320
that people aren't going to get like really angry with you right away.

00:41:36.320 --> 00:41:39.439
They're going to be like, OK, well, you know, there's a little bit of

00:41:39.439 --> 00:41:45.320
suffering now, but this person saved me so much time that it's not so bad.

00:41:46.439 --> 00:41:47.679
But yeah, it's really hard.

00:41:47.679 --> 00:41:50.800
And particularly as you're starting out, like you're going to make mistakes

00:41:50.800 --> 00:41:54.439
like that's inevitable and you're going to do things that when you look back

00:41:54.439 --> 00:41:59.320
a year later, you're like, why on earth did I do it that way?

00:42:00.239 --> 00:42:03.479
And now you want to like rip out the whole thing and write it from scratch.

00:42:03.479 --> 00:42:08.439
And I think that like if it feels horrible, but you have to remember,

00:42:08.439 --> 00:42:12.080
like that's great because it means you've grown immensely as a programmer.

00:42:12.280 --> 00:42:15.879
And certainly if you have like my kind of mindset, you have to like resist

00:42:15.879 --> 00:42:19.959
the temptation to like rip things out and redo them as much as possible

00:42:20.199 --> 00:42:23.360
and just focus on making the next generation better

00:42:23.760 --> 00:42:26.959
rather than breaking what what what stuff people already have.

00:42:27.320 --> 00:42:30.360
So I don't have any great answers there, but I think you've just got to think

00:42:30.360 --> 00:42:34.399
about those tensions of like, how do I keep my forward velocity up

00:42:34.399 --> 00:42:40.320
while getting better as a programmer while evolving over time?

00:42:40.320 --> 00:42:44.239
But, you know, things and also thinking about how do you make the things

00:42:44.239 --> 00:42:46.679
you did a long time ago better.

00:42:46.679 --> 00:42:47.600
Thank you for that.

00:42:47.600 --> 00:42:48.040
Thank you.

00:42:48.040 --> 00:42:51.600
I see there are a few questions that mention

00:42:52.120 --> 00:42:56.159
ChatGPT, one was from Ian.

00:42:56.879 --> 00:43:00.399
Ianson, what is your opinion on how it will evolve

00:43:00.399 --> 00:43:02.800
the data scientist's role in an organization?

00:43:03.080 --> 00:43:06.520
I will caveat my remarks with I

00:43:07.719 --> 00:43:11.399
I would say 99% of my ChatGPT

00:43:11.399 --> 00:43:13.959
use is entirely frivolous.

00:43:15.120 --> 00:43:16.840
I use it to make things rhyme.

00:43:16.840 --> 00:43:19.280
I use it to make things sound like pirates.

00:43:20.320 --> 00:43:23.320
I use it to make things sound like southern grandmas

00:43:23.320 --> 00:43:26.600
who use a lot of country folk sayings.

00:43:27.080 --> 00:43:30.080
I use it to make acrostics of people's names.

00:43:31.120 --> 00:43:34.800
I use it now with the finance person I work with.

00:43:34.800 --> 00:43:39.760
I submit requests exclusively in the form of office screenplays.

00:43:42.320 --> 00:43:45.760
So I like I don't know, I think it's like incredibly fun

00:43:45.959 --> 00:43:50.360
for stuff like that when I try to use it for programming.

00:43:52.159 --> 00:43:55.840
It's been like hit or miss, like sometimes it's great

00:43:56.360 --> 00:44:01.439
and sometimes it spits out something that looks like totally plausible,

00:44:01.439 --> 00:44:03.879
but is utterly wrong.

00:44:03.879 --> 00:44:05.840
So it's and it's hard for me to tell.

00:44:05.840 --> 00:44:09.760
Like, is that just like is that ChatGPT today?

00:44:09.760 --> 00:44:12.199
And like in a year's time, it's going to be much better.

00:44:12.600 --> 00:44:15.080
Or is it going to be like self-driving cars

00:44:15.080 --> 00:44:18.239
where they're kind of always coming like a year in the future

00:44:18.560 --> 00:44:20.600
and we never quite get there?

00:44:22.320 --> 00:44:25.639
Self-driving cars is something I think about a lot because I have a Tesla

00:44:25.959 --> 00:44:29.399
and whenever I park it in the garage, it thinks the random collection

00:44:29.399 --> 00:44:34.000
of tools hanging on the wall is a semi like about to crash into us.

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:37.520
And I'm like, it can't even handle like this.

00:44:37.520 --> 00:44:39.879
And people say we're going to have self-driving cars.

00:44:40.719 --> 00:44:42.840
So so I don't know, it's hard for me to say.

00:44:42.840 --> 00:44:45.600
I'd say overall, I'm kind of like a skeptic.

00:44:46.360 --> 00:44:47.800
I think it is going to be useful.

00:44:47.800 --> 00:44:51.320
I think it's particularly probably hard for me to say, like in some ways,

00:44:51.320 --> 00:44:53.600
it's going to be really useful when you're learning,

00:44:53.600 --> 00:44:58.000
because you can take the things that are words in your head and spit them out

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:02.399
and say, like, how do I rotate the X axis labels on the ggplot

00:45:02.399 --> 00:45:07.080
and get something pretty reasonable, which makes it super useful for learning.

00:45:07.320 --> 00:45:10.239
But at the same time, as you're learning, it's going to spit out stuff

00:45:10.239 --> 00:45:13.199
that looks totally plausible, but it's totally wrong.

00:45:13.199 --> 00:45:17.479
And you're in the worst possible situation to try and figure out what's going on.

00:45:17.479 --> 00:45:20.120
So I don't know. We'll see.

00:45:20.120 --> 00:45:21.439
I think it's super exciting.

00:45:21.439 --> 00:45:24.840
I have a lot of fun with it, but I do not use it all professionally.

00:45:25.159 --> 00:45:28.760
It seems like there's a lot of people who think those are great use cases of it

00:45:29.320 --> 00:45:31.479
the way you're using it.

00:45:33.479 --> 00:45:35.280
Let me go over.

00:45:35.280 --> 00:45:38.520
I will say I recently we had a company meeting recently

00:45:38.520 --> 00:45:41.120
where some customers come on and I took their bios

00:45:41.600 --> 00:45:44.639
and just made chat GPT make them rhyme.

00:45:44.639 --> 00:45:49.000
And the people were like so impressed, so impressed.

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:51.560
I'm like, I just made chat GPT make it rhyme.

00:45:52.639 --> 00:45:57.439
I see there's a lot of conversation beneath Yu's question.

00:45:57.560 --> 00:45:59.479
Yu, do you want to jump in here?

00:45:59.479 --> 00:46:02.719
Hi. Hi, Helene. Nice to meet you. Big fan of your work.

00:46:03.159 --> 00:46:08.280
So my question is, what's the implementation plan of R on cloud computing platforms?

00:46:08.280 --> 00:46:10.199
So my team works in Azure.

00:46:10.199 --> 00:46:13.199
And how do we say using R there is very inconvenient at best.

00:46:13.679 --> 00:46:17.199
So previously, before we moved to Azure, the work of my team,

00:46:17.199 --> 00:46:19.719
I would say 70% in R, 30% in Python.

00:46:19.959 --> 00:46:25.000
After moving to Azure, I quickly changed to 70% in Python, 30% in R.

00:46:25.360 --> 00:46:29.159
So Python is just a very natural option for modeling analysis there.

00:46:29.159 --> 00:46:32.120
So how do you plan to change this in the future?

00:46:32.360 --> 00:46:36.719
Yeah, I mean, I don't know if change is quite the right phrase,

00:46:36.719 --> 00:46:38.959
because I don't know if we have the power to do that.

00:46:38.959 --> 00:46:42.719
But certainly, you know, what we are trying to do is make R

00:46:42.719 --> 00:46:46.800
as easy as possible to use everywhere you can possibly use it.

00:46:47.679 --> 00:46:51.040
And, you know, I think thinking about like as more and more people move to cloud

00:46:51.040 --> 00:46:54.280
computing, how can we make it easy to get set up and get configured

00:46:54.280 --> 00:46:57.159
and make things just work is really important.

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:01.080
I know like one example at the moment is we're working on a partnership

00:47:01.360 --> 00:47:07.080
with Databricks to make using R inside Databricks clusters much, much easier.

00:47:08.040 --> 00:47:12.600
Certainly, like this seems like there's a lot of like just challenges

00:47:12.600 --> 00:47:16.080
getting things set up there that, you know, folks have kind of solved

00:47:16.080 --> 00:47:20.840
on the Python side and no one has put the time into solving on the R side.

00:47:20.840 --> 00:47:23.600
So I'm hoping that, you know, as a company, we'll continue to invest

00:47:24.280 --> 00:47:27.760
in those opportunities, just make it easy to use for everyone.

00:47:28.600 --> 00:47:33.280
Lisa, I see you had a question earlier on ggplot2, do you want to jump in?

00:47:33.520 --> 00:47:38.080
Sure. I think I have two questions about ggplot2, but I think I'll go with the first one,

00:47:38.080 --> 00:47:41.840
which is sort of how do you feel about

00:47:42.959 --> 00:47:46.800
people contributing, having so many people

00:47:47.320 --> 00:47:51.600
contributing to that package and like all the add-ons that have come from it?

00:47:52.760 --> 00:47:56.560
Sort of like any any things that sort of amazed you

00:47:56.560 --> 00:48:00.840
and then on the opposite side, any sort of major frustrations?

00:48:01.080 --> 00:48:06.600
Yeah, I mean, I think the thing that's kind of kind of blows my mind about ggplot2

00:48:06.600 --> 00:48:12.080
is it's like coming up to it's going to come up to its 18th birthday fairly soon.

00:48:12.080 --> 00:48:15.239
So I'm sort of joking about that will be time to like emancipate it.

00:48:15.239 --> 00:48:19.000
And that's going to just have to like survive by itself from now on.

00:48:20.840 --> 00:48:24.560
And kind of realistically, like I'm not that involved in the day to day

00:48:25.280 --> 00:48:27.360
management of ggplot2 anymore.

00:48:27.360 --> 00:48:31.120
That torch is going to be passed to Thomas Peterson.

00:48:31.120 --> 00:48:34.000
It was now, you know, starting to get, you know, like, I guess

00:48:35.479 --> 00:48:38.719
four years ago, I was like sick of maintaining ggplot2.

00:48:39.080 --> 00:48:41.479
I've been long ago, sick of maintaining a hired Thomas.

00:48:41.479 --> 00:48:43.800
And now Thomas is getting sick of maintaining it.

00:48:43.879 --> 00:48:46.199
So we've got to like figure out what to do next.

00:48:47.239 --> 00:48:51.280
But yeah, like maintaining something that is like so popular

00:48:51.840 --> 00:48:54.879
is, you know, both a blessing and a curse.

00:48:54.879 --> 00:48:58.679
It's like incredible to know that, you know, literally millions of people

00:48:58.679 --> 00:49:03.320
have used it and it's helped them, you know, make graphs and make your life easier.

00:49:03.879 --> 00:49:07.639
But it also is like immensely challenging to make any changes

00:49:07.639 --> 00:49:12.719
because like so many people rely on it now and are used to the defaults.

00:49:13.159 --> 00:49:15.560
So there's there's something like I think both.

00:49:17.199 --> 00:49:20.239
I don't know if I can quickly pull this off, but like one thing I think about

00:49:20.239 --> 00:49:25.120
a little. A little bit from time to time, it's just like how many people

00:49:25.760 --> 00:49:28.520
like if I find the most.

00:49:28.520 --> 00:49:32.320
Popular, yeah, so the most popular page on the ggplot2

00:49:32.320 --> 00:49:34.879
website is the Geom Bar documentation,

00:49:35.600 --> 00:49:39.919
which 15,000 people have read in the last month.

00:49:40.919 --> 00:49:43.919
Like there are not many ways you can reach, like

00:49:43.919 --> 00:49:47.639
you can have more of an impact on people's lives by looking at that page

00:49:47.639 --> 00:49:50.320
about bar charts and thinking, how can we make that better?

00:49:52.040 --> 00:49:56.080
But at the same time, those changes tend to be kind of small and incremental.

00:49:56.080 --> 00:50:01.320
So it's also like fun to like, you know, embark on completely new projects

00:50:01.320 --> 00:50:05.159
that no one uses, so you're free to do whatever you want.

00:50:06.040 --> 00:50:09.560
And in some ways, I think like the ecosystem of packages

00:50:10.040 --> 00:50:13.320
is kind of it takes a combination of those strengths and those weaknesses

00:50:13.320 --> 00:50:17.879
because like ggplot2 can like stay the same and stable,

00:50:18.320 --> 00:50:21.199
whereas you can continue to like build on top of it

00:50:21.199 --> 00:50:24.840
with these packages that fewer people use, but are also like much more

00:50:25.159 --> 00:50:27.479
easier to change and flexible.

00:50:27.639 --> 00:50:31.840
So I definitely have like mixed feelings about like this.

00:50:32.120 --> 00:50:35.560
But both like it's awesome, like when people use my stuff

00:50:36.120 --> 00:50:38.600
and you know, that just feels so good.

00:50:38.600 --> 00:50:42.120
But it's also like, oh, now I have to like answer their questions

00:50:42.120 --> 00:50:44.040
and I can't just change things willy nilly.

00:50:44.040 --> 00:50:46.760
So I also do like working on things that no one uses.

00:50:46.919 --> 00:50:49.280
That's also a different a different kind of fun.

00:50:49.600 --> 00:50:53.600
At least something that's like stood out in my mind that I've learned

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:59.399
from you from internal company calls is how you handle focus time

00:50:59.399 --> 00:51:01.959
and the way you you manage your own time.

00:51:02.760 --> 00:51:05.600
And I thought it might be helpful just to chat a little bit about that

00:51:05.600 --> 00:51:07.479
and to share how you think about that.

00:51:07.479 --> 00:51:12.040
Yeah, I once sort of one funny anecdote, I gave a talk about this idea

00:51:12.040 --> 00:51:15.879
of focus time and a couple of years ago, probably now at the company.

00:51:15.879 --> 00:51:20.560
And I was like, I feel like the truest expression of my philosophy

00:51:20.560 --> 00:51:23.719
would be to say, no, I'm not going to give a talk about focus time

00:51:23.719 --> 00:51:26.479
because that's going to interrupt my work for the day.

00:51:27.760 --> 00:51:32.560
But I really try to like create a lot of time

00:51:32.560 --> 00:51:37.239
for like uninterrupted work, because I think, you know, like programming

00:51:37.239 --> 00:51:40.040
is like fundamentally creative work

00:51:41.040 --> 00:51:45.639
and like finding the time to kind of like process

00:51:45.639 --> 00:51:48.719
and think things through is is really important.

00:51:51.040 --> 00:51:55.760
So what my what I do currently is I like every day, as I said, I try

00:51:55.760 --> 00:51:59.719
and like first thing I do, I get up and write for a couple of hours

00:51:59.719 --> 00:52:00.639
or an hour at least.

00:52:02.000 --> 00:52:05.080
That's like the time of the day where I am most productive.

00:52:05.080 --> 00:52:08.040
And so I want to spend on the things I think are most important,

00:52:08.719 --> 00:52:11.239
you know, not the things that are necessary, most urgent.

00:52:12.479 --> 00:52:15.800
And then, you know, I have a team, so I have to I have to talk to them.

00:52:16.239 --> 00:52:21.159
But and I have to talk to my colleagues that, of course, I love talking to.

00:52:21.159 --> 00:52:23.280
But it means I can't do other work.

00:52:23.280 --> 00:52:27.399
So my kind of compromise is I've got two days a week off on my calendar,

00:52:27.719 --> 00:52:32.280
Tuesdays and Thursdays, where I try really, really hard not to do these things.

00:52:32.679 --> 00:52:35.760
You know, sometimes if there's like a bigger meeting, there's like 15 people

00:52:35.760 --> 00:52:36.959
and it's impossible to find the time.

00:52:36.959 --> 00:52:37.919
Otherwise, I'll do it.

00:52:37.919 --> 00:52:42.439
But I really generally pretty good about keeping those days clear

00:52:42.439 --> 00:52:44.760
so I can tackle bigger problems.

00:52:45.239 --> 00:52:48.080
And I think that's, you know, really important.

00:52:48.560 --> 00:52:51.280
It's it's, of course, challenging because you have when you've got a big

00:52:51.280 --> 00:52:54.399
four hour block of time, you still have to like train yourself to like

00:52:54.879 --> 00:52:57.840
resist the temptations of TikTok and

00:52:59.399 --> 00:53:02.280
Mastodon or certainly that

00:53:02.280 --> 00:53:06.439
temptation of Twitter has been totally removed from me today these days.

00:53:06.439 --> 00:53:08.479
So I guess that's good.

00:53:09.760 --> 00:53:12.919
But certainly, like you have to train yourself to like, you know, hard

00:53:12.919 --> 00:53:17.719
to like stay focused on one thing and not given to all the other

00:53:17.719 --> 00:53:19.639
more fun distractions that you have around you.

00:53:19.639 --> 00:53:22.679
But giving yourself that space, I think, is really important.

00:53:22.800 --> 00:53:24.560
Thank you so much.

00:53:24.560 --> 00:53:27.919
I know this hour always goes by very quickly

00:53:28.159 --> 00:53:30.199
and there's so many great questions.

00:53:30.199 --> 00:53:34.360
So maybe I can collect those and share them with you at some point, Hadley,

00:53:34.360 --> 00:53:36.679
and we can think about how to answer them all.

00:53:39.199 --> 00:53:41.879
But another question I'd love to ask you is,

00:53:42.600 --> 00:53:47.840
are there any books you'd recommend to this audience here or resources

00:53:47.840 --> 00:53:51.479
you'd recommend that have been useful for you in your career?

00:53:52.120 --> 00:53:55.840
Yeah, let me show you if I can find.

00:53:57.959 --> 00:54:00.439
The ones I like the most, I keep around.

00:54:00.439 --> 00:54:04.760
Yeah. This is one of the books that's kind of been inspiring

00:54:04.760 --> 00:54:08.479
or has inspired the Tidyverse design book.

00:54:08.479 --> 00:54:09.959
It's called A Pattern Language.

00:54:09.959 --> 00:54:13.600
It's actually a book about architecture and how you design houses.

00:54:15.560 --> 00:54:18.439
It's just a really like, you know, it's a very thick book,

00:54:18.439 --> 00:54:20.080
but it's designed to be kind of skimmable.

00:54:20.080 --> 00:54:23.120
I think it's just sort of fun and interesting to read about.

00:54:23.120 --> 00:54:26.159
And this like system of describing all of these components,

00:54:26.159 --> 00:54:27.879
it's really interesting to read about.

00:54:28.439 --> 00:54:32.239
of describing all of these components, the different levels of hierarchy

00:54:32.560 --> 00:54:35.479
and how you can join them together, I think is very much

00:54:36.280 --> 00:54:38.639
connected to programming.

00:54:39.120 --> 00:54:43.919
I'll also say like one, one reason I stopped reading physical books

00:54:44.639 --> 00:54:48.360
is like, I look at these books now and I'm like, oh, my God,

00:54:48.600 --> 00:54:50.560
why is the font so small?

00:54:50.560 --> 00:54:52.760
But it's because I am

00:54:53.919 --> 00:54:57.320
becoming middle aged and becoming increasingly short sighted,

00:54:57.320 --> 00:54:58.080
which sucks.

00:55:03.080 --> 00:55:06.760
I don't know, I think that's the book I've been thinking about like the most

00:55:07.639 --> 00:55:10.040
lately, some of the other ones, I guess I've

00:55:12.080 --> 00:55:16.000
gotten rid of because I have limited book space

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:17.879
and I kind of like keeping these.

00:55:17.879 --> 00:55:19.840
I'm also this collection of like,

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:24.679
you know, fairly historical books.

00:55:24.679 --> 00:55:29.080
This is like from 1923, because there's just so much.

00:55:31.280 --> 00:55:34.679
When you kind of look back at what people were doing

00:55:34.679 --> 00:55:38.760
like 100 years ago, like I think it's really revealing

00:55:38.760 --> 00:55:43.719
that in many cases, like the quality of visualizations

00:55:44.120 --> 00:55:48.840
is not improved that much, like the quality of the best visualizations

00:55:48.840 --> 00:55:51.879
is not improved a huge amount in the last 100 years.

00:55:52.000 --> 00:55:57.280
But the ease of making them like now you can like whip out 15 variations

00:55:57.280 --> 00:56:01.520
and GG plot in 15 minutes, whereas before you were like painstakingly

00:56:01.520 --> 00:56:03.239
draw them all out with pen and ink.

00:56:03.239 --> 00:56:07.479
So I think it's just sort of interesting to reflect on that a little bit.

00:56:07.479 --> 00:56:12.120
And like what's what's changed really in visualization in the last 100 years?

00:56:12.120 --> 00:56:15.760
I know we're at the end here, but maybe one inspirational

00:56:16.439 --> 00:56:19.800
question to ask you, what's something that you're

00:56:19.800 --> 00:56:22.439
you're most excited about as you think about

00:56:23.439 --> 00:56:25.919
the tidyverse and Posit going forward?

00:56:25.919 --> 00:56:32.080
And I am like legitimately really excited about us embracing Python more.

00:56:32.080 --> 00:56:37.000
You know, I'm still using Python, but I went to a Python conference

00:56:37.000 --> 00:56:39.840
recently and talked to a bunch of people using Python.

00:56:40.360 --> 00:56:44.879
And I'm just excited about helping out all these Python using data scientists

00:56:44.879 --> 00:56:48.199
because it just feels like this Posit, you know, it's like,

00:56:48.199 --> 00:56:53.159
it feels like this Posit, like it just works type stuff.

00:56:53.159 --> 00:56:55.760
There's just a huge, huge scope for that.

00:56:55.760 --> 00:56:59.159
And I'm excited to kind of help spread that like

00:56:59.679 --> 00:57:03.399
the Posit way of doing things, the Posit kind of community,

00:57:03.879 --> 00:57:08.679
how we think about people and try and spread that further and further in the world.

00:57:08.679 --> 00:57:10.159
Thank you so much, Hadley.

00:57:10.159 --> 00:57:11.959
Is that our new slogan? It just works.

00:57:12.840 --> 00:57:14.439
I think it should be.

00:57:15.040 --> 00:57:17.760
We're not like, we're certainly not there everywhere,

00:57:17.760 --> 00:57:22.560
but I just think that's like, that's what the best experience you can deliver.

00:57:22.560 --> 00:57:24.719
You just try something out and it works.

00:57:25.159 --> 00:57:28.840
And people stop remarking on that because it just works.

00:57:28.840 --> 00:57:30.159
They don't have to think about that.

00:57:30.159 --> 00:57:34.199
And I think that's, I will say, I think some of the best packages

00:57:34.600 --> 00:57:37.679
that me and my team have created are almost invisible

00:57:37.679 --> 00:57:41.639
because they just make problems go away and you never need to think about them.

00:57:41.639 --> 00:57:44.239
You never need to know about them because that's just some pain.

00:57:44.239 --> 00:57:46.360
You never need to experience.

00:57:46.360 --> 00:57:48.879
And then you can just listen to all the old

00:57:48.879 --> 00:57:52.239
thoughts cranking on about how terrible it was back in the day

00:57:52.239 --> 00:57:56.159
and how they had to trudge barefoot to school and three feet of snow

00:57:56.159 --> 00:57:58.320
and just listen to their stories and be happy.

00:57:58.760 --> 00:58:01.000
You don't live in that environment anymore.

00:58:02.040 --> 00:58:04.879
Thank you so much again for joining us today, Hadley.

00:58:04.879 --> 00:58:08.800
And thank you all so much for for joining the hangout today

00:58:08.800 --> 00:58:11.239
and and making this space what it is.

00:58:11.639 --> 00:58:14.919
Pretty impressive to have over 200 people on a Zoom call

00:58:14.919 --> 00:58:17.040
and not have to worry about what's happening.

00:58:17.040 --> 00:58:20.560
And thank you all for monitoring the space, too.

00:58:21.360 --> 00:58:25.800
If this was your first hangout, we would absolutely love to have you join us again.

00:58:25.800 --> 00:58:30.760
So again, they happen every Thursday, same time, same place.

00:58:32.120 --> 00:58:37.080
I'll put the link again where you can just add it to your calendar.

00:58:37.639 --> 00:58:40.760
But next week, we'll be joined by Mike Lopez,

00:58:40.760 --> 00:58:44.360
senior director of football data and analytics at the NFL.

00:58:45.320 --> 00:58:47.479
So he'll be our feature leader next week.

00:58:48.360 --> 00:58:53.159
And if you have any questions about it or want to reach out to me,

00:58:53.159 --> 00:58:55.320
feel free to connect on LinkedIn as well.

00:58:56.520 --> 00:59:00.439
Thank you all so much for joining today and have a great,

00:59:00.439 --> 00:59:02.840
great rest of the day, great rest of the week.

00:59:02.840 --> 00:59:03.959
Bye, everybody.

